Species Comments: *NOT A SABINE'S GULL,* Confirmed Laughing Gull. Updated info for educational purposes:  Four main indicators, even with this blurry image, that this is not a Sabine's Gull, but rather a young juvenile Laughing Gull-- 1. Most importantly, long bill, giving head a longer look rather than the "snouty" look of the Sabine's; 2. Lacks the well-defined white forehead and throat, instead with a light gray around face and eyes; 3. Gray crossing breast rather than restricted to upper breast; 4. Lack of neat Sabine's scaling on back.    Thanks to reviewers Louis Bevier and Luke Seitz for feedback.    Original comment: Unconfirmed ID-- Off of rocks at Reid state park directly to the left of entrance to beach. ~40ft off shore with ring-billed gulls, herring gulls, and eiders. Probably 2/3 the size of a ring bill or smaller with marks matching pics of juveniles from internet. We also noted a gull (perhaps the same one?) with a notable v marks on wings, further suggesting Sabine's over possible juv. laughing gull. White breast and relatively dark back near tail.

Based on the placement of other "meow" calls just before this individual was sighted, there is the narrow possibility of a second bird, although that's far from confirmed.
